description: This is a Geodesic Dome--in Brooklyn.  And despite the urban setting it is a completely private oasis, reached through a hidden doorway and invisible from the street. Amenities include private outdoor space, hand-made furniture, a sauna, a vintage quadrophonic stereo system, a wood-burning stove, and, optionally (for an extra charge, with signature of a waiver, on a case-by-case basis), usage of a private pool. It is a perfect place for a couple or any adventurous person.

hosts.about: I’ve lived in NYC since college (The New School for Social Research, class of 1994) and came here with one goal: to become a writer. To me this was the single city in America where literature and art were valued above all else.  And it was a place full of unconventional real estate.  Downtown Lofts, Lower East Side walkup—the way people lived was an extension of the creative existence.  I lived on an old passenger ferryboat at the end of N. Moore Street in Tribeca.  But eventually (like most every writer or artist) I migrated across the water and into Brooklyn.  I also had kids.  What I love about Brooklyn, and this part of it in particular, is that Bohemia and creativity are still alive, and there’s a Waldorf school right across the street.

house_rules:
• Check in is anytime after 3PM
• May not be safe or suitable for children (0-12 years)
• No parties or events
• Not suitable for pets

- There is a spiral staircase with variable tread heights--be careful!

review.comments: The dome was a unique experience that I would highly recommend to anyone looking for an unconventional place to stay in Bedstuy. Perfect space for a creative retreat, and I doubt there is anything like it anywhere else in Brooklyn. Sean was great at communicating exactly what to expect, and was very flexible accommodating to our slightly hectic schedule when arriving.
